Firms. The financial structure of the firms is basically determined by two parameters: the ratio of own capital over total wage bill (h) and the average number of TFR payments that are kept within the firms (k), both measuring how much the firms can rely on these sources of credit before going bankrupt. Each firm is also defined by its size, by the presence or absence of an agreement with an occupational PF, and by the degree of information (
α
) which is shared among the employees.16 The values of the parameters for the firms are summarized in Table 4 .

Finally, some words should be spent on the role of information (parameter 

α

). Our simulation analysis for the postreform scenario covers a period of two years, and in this time span, as we can see in the Figure 4, the effect of this parameter on the aggregate adhesion rate is positive, although its relevance is more remarkable for low levels of information. For example, an increase of information from 0.1 to 0.4 produces a 2 percentage increase in the adhesion rates to the second pillar. Beyond such values of information, the same increase in adhesion rates can only be obtained from a raise of α from 0.4 to 1.
